# Complete Competitive Programming Journey on HackerEarth  
Beginner → Intermediate → Advanced (2026 Edition)

A structured, self-paced roadmap to go from "I don't know coding" to solving 1900+ rated problems on HackerEarth / similar platforms.

## Who is this for?
- Zero to low experience in coding
- College students preparing for placements / internships
- Anyone who wants strong problem-solving & DSA skills
- People who find LeetCode too dry and want more beginner-friendly tutorials + contests

**Main Platform:** [HackerEarth Practice](https://www.hackerearth.com/practice/)  
→ Excellent tutorials + categorized problems + monthly contests

## Phase 0: Choose Your Language (1–3 weeks)
Pick **one** language and become comfortable writing & debugging code.

Recommended order (easiest → powerful):
1. **Python** → very beginner friendly (recommended for absolute beginners)
2. **C++**   → fastest & most used in competitive programming (recommended after basics)
3. Java / others → only if you already know them

**Goal:**  
- Variables, loops, if-else, functions, arrays/strings  
- Input / Output correctly (very important on HackerEarth!)

**HackerEarth starting points:**
- [Basics of Input/Output](https://www.hackerearth.com/practice/basic-programming/input-output/basics-of-input-output/)
- [Basics of Implementation](https://www.hackerearth.com/practice/basic-programming/implementation/basics-of-implementation/)

**Practice:** Solve 30–50 very easy problems from **Basic Programming** section.

## Phase 1: Beginner Level – Build Logic & Confidence (1–3 months)
Focus → Simple patterns, math tricks, implementation

**Main Topics & HackerEarth Sections**
1. **Basic Programming** track (start here!)
   - Input/Output
   - Implementation
   - Operators & Bitwise
   - Recursion (very basic)

2. **Math** section
   - Number Theory basics (GCD, LCM, Prime, Modular)
   - [Basic Number Theory - 1](https://www.hackerearth.com/practice/math/basic-number-theory-1/)

3. **Arrays & Strings** (1-D)
   - [1-D Arrays](https://www.hackerearth.com/practice/data-structures/arrays/1-d/)

**Milestones to achieve**
- Solve 150–200 easy problems
- Participate in 4–5 **HackerEarth Circuits** (monthly beginner-friendly contest)
- Comfortable with time limit \~1s & 256MB memory

**Tips**
- Read problem statement 2–3 times
- Dry run on paper with small examples
- Use Python first if stuck → later convert to C++

## Phase 2: Intermediate Level – Core Data Structures & Algorithms (3–8 months)
Now things get serious.

**Must-learn order (with HackerEarth sections)**

| Order | Topic                          | HackerEarth Section / Tutorial                              | Approx. Problems |
|-------|--------------------------------|---------------------------------------------------------------------|------------------|
| 1     | Time & Space Complexity        | Read articles + watch any 15-min video                     | —                |
| 2     | Arrays + Sorting + Searching   | 1-D, Multi-dimensional, Sorting section                    | 80–120           |
| 3     | Stacks & Queues                | [Basics of Stacks](https://www.hackerearth.com/practice/data-structures/stacks/basics-of-stacks/) <br>Basics of Queues | 40–70            |
| 4     | Hashing / Maps                 | [Basics of Hash Tables](https://www.hackerearth.com/practice/data-structures/hash-tables/basics-of-hash-tables/) | 40–80            |
| 5     | Binary Search & Two Pointers   | Practice in Arrays & Math sections                         | 50–80            |
| 6     | Recursion + Backtracking       | [Recursion and Backtracking](https://www.hackerearth.com/practice/basic-programming/recursion/recursion-and-backtracking/) | 40–70            |
| 7     | Greedy Algorithms              | Greedy section + many implementation problems              | 50–90            |
| 8     | Basic Bit Manipulation         | Bit section + problems                                     | 30–60            |

**Milestones**
- Solve 400–600 medium-level problems
- Reach **HackerEarth rating \~1400–1600**
- Solve at least 2–3 medium problems in every contest
- Start **CodeMonk** tracks on HackerEarth (very well structured)

## Phase 3: Advanced Level – Expert Competitive Programmer (8+ months)
Goal: Solve hard problems quickly, understand editorials fast

**Advanced Topics (learn in this order)**

1. **Binary Search on Answer** + Ternary Search
2. **Advanced Number Theory** (Sieve variants, Modular Inverse, Euler Totient, Chinese Remainder)
3. **Graph Algorithms**
   - BFS / DFS
   - Shortest Path (Dijkstra, Bellman-Ford)
   - MST (Kruskal + Prim)
   - Topological Sort
   - Strongly Connected Components

4. **Dynamic Programming** (the game changer)
   - 1D DP
   - 2D DP
   - DP on Trees
   - Digit DP
   - Bitmask DP

5. **Advanced Data Structures**
   - Segment Tree / Fenwick Tree (Binary Indexed Tree)
   - Trie
   - Disjoint Set Union (with path compression + union by rank)

6. **Strings Advanced**
   - KMP / Z-algorithm
   - Suffix Array / Suffix Automata (optional for very high level)

**Practice Strategy**
- Solve **HackerEarth Algorithms** section → 976+ problems!
- Solve previous **HackerEarth long challenges** (5-day contests)
- Upsolve every contest you participate in
- Read editorials even if you solved the problem

**Target**
- Consistent top 20–30% in HackerEarth contests
- Rating 1800+ on HackerEarth / equivalent \~1900+ Codeforces

## Recommended Habits
- Solve at least 4–5 problems every day
- Participate in **every** HackerEarth contest possible
- Make a **public list** of solved problems (this repo!)
- Revise weak topics every 2–3 weeks
- Help others in discussion → you learn more

